Hey   they sold SVB:

First Citizens BancShares Inc. agreed to buy Silicon Valley Bank after a ru=
n on deposits wiped out the company in the biggest US bank failure in more =
than a decade.
The deal to settle SVB=E2=80=99s fate could help tamp down some of the turm=
oil that has engulfed the financial world, and shares of regional banks ral=
lied on the news, with First Citizens up 44%. The Federal Deposit Insurance=
 Corp. seized SVB earlier this month amid concern that bank runs could spre=
ad.
The acquisition transforms First Citizens into one of the top 15 US banks, =
according to Bloomberg Intelligence, with help from some favorable terms. F=
irst Citizens is buying about $72 billion of SVB=E2=80=99s assets at a disc=
ount of $16.5 billion, according to an FDIC statement.
This leaves about $90 billion in securities and other SVB assets in the han=
ds of the FDIC, and an estimated cost of the failure to the Deposit Insuran=
ce Fund of about $20 billion. Meanwhile, the FDIC gets equity appreciation =
rights in First Citizens with a potential value of $500 million.

The financing of the deal is sort of fascinating.
  [4]
=C2=A0First Citizens is getting about $110.1 billion of assets, including $=
35 billion of cash and $72 billion of loans. In exchange, it is putting up =
zero dollars and assuming about $93.6 billion of liabilities, for a total p=
urchase price for those assets of negative $16.5 billion.=C2=A0
The liabilities consist mainly of:
=09$56.5 billion of SVB deposits, and=09a $35 billion five-year promissory =
note to the FDIC with 3.5% interest.

There is also a series of deals to share the upside and downside. On the do=
wnside, First Citizens bears the risk of the first $5 billion of losses on =
the portfolio, but the FDIC shares any additional losses 50/50. On the upsi=
de, if there=C2=A0are=C2=A0no additional losses, First Citizens has to give=
 the FDIC some money back, up to $1.5 billion; the FDIC also gets a =E2=80=
=9Cvalue appreciation instrument=E2=80=9D giving it some upside in First Ci=
tizens=E2=80=99 stock, capped at $500 million.
  [5]

Arguably   the basic problem at SVB was that it had a portfolio of long-ter=
m assets (loans, Treasury bonds, etc.) supported by rickety short-term fina=
ncing: SVB was funded mainly by deposits, almost all of which exceeded the =
FDIC=E2=80=99s deposit insurance cap of $250,000 per account. When deposito=
rs got nervous, they took out a lot of money all at once =E2=80=94=C2=A0$42=
 billion in one day =E2=80=94=C2=A0and SVB didn=E2=80=99t have enough money=
 to pay them.
The basic fix for this is pretty much to get some long-term funding =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0ideally=C2=A0cheap=C2=A0long-term funding, since SVB loaded up on =
long-dated assets back when interest rates were very low, and would be losi=
ng money if it had to borrow at 5% to fund them. And that is in fact what h=
appened. SVB=E2=80=99s $90 billion securities portfolio now belongs to the =
FDIC, which is the US government and gets very cheap funding.=C2=A0
And its loan portfolio now belongs to First Citizens, which is paying for i=
t by borrowing $35 billion from the FDIC for five years at 3.5% interest. A=
s the loans pay off, First Citizens will send the money to the FDIC,
  [6]
=C2=A0but there is no rush; the long-term financing from the FDIC means tha=
t First Citizens doesn=E2=80=99t need to worry about getting cash before it=
s loans mature. Also the money is cheap: The US government can borrow for f=
ive years at about 3.58%, but First Citizens is doing a bit better borrowin=
g from the government.
Of course the other $56.5 billion of First Citizens=E2=80=99 financing come=
s from SVB=E2=80=99s depositors who haven=E2=80=99t taken their money out y=
et. That =E2=80=A6=C2=A0might be shorter-term money?=C2=A0As of Dec. 31, 20=
22, Silicon Valley Bank had about $173 billion of deposits,=C2=A0of which a=
bout $165 billion were not insured by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., =
mostly because they exceeded the $250,000 cap on FDIC insurance.
  [7]
=C2=A0As of this morning, after its bank run, it had about $56.5 billion of=
 deposits. I don=E2=80=99t know how many of those deposits are uninsured, b=
ut I would be surprised if people were flocking=C2=A0to=C2=A0Silicon Valley=
 bank to deposit money in the last couple of weeks, so my guess is that no =
more than $8 billion of deposits (the rough number as of Dec. 31) are insur=
ed, and the remaining $48.5 billion are not. For the last two weeks, SVB ha=
s been,=C2=A0and has   advertised itself as, the safest bank in the US: It =
was essentially the only bank where all deposits, even those way above the =
FDIC=E2=80=99s $250,000 deposit-insurance cap, were guaranteed by the FDIC.
  [8]
=C2=A0Now, uh, things are back to normal I guess? =E2=80=9CAll deposits ass=
umed by First=E2=80=93Citizens Bank & Trust Company will continue to be ins=
ured by the FDIC up to the insurance limit,=E2=80=9D says  the FDIC=E2=80=
=99s announcement, which is a limit that did not exist at SVB last week.

