We   talked last week about the discovery that some nickel belonging to JPM=
organ Chase & Co., which it used to support nickel futures trading on the L=
ondon Metal Exchange, was actually just rocks. The nickel =E2=80=94=C2=A0I =
mean, rocks =E2=80=94 had been sitting in an LME-affiliated warehouse for y=
ears; its role in life was to support nickel futures trading, not to be tur=
ned into batteries or cars or whatever. =E2=80=9CThe nickel worked perfectl=
y well for those purposes =E2=80=94 JPMorgan=E2=80=99s derivative contracts=
 traded and paid off normally =E2=80=94 for years, even though the nickel w=
as not in fact nickel, just bags of rocks,=E2=80=9D I wrote. I went on:
And then one day a warehouse worker, like, stubbed his toe against JPMorgan=
=E2=80=99s nickel and was like =E2=80=9Chmm that=E2=80=99s not the sound ni=
ckel makes when you kick it=E2=80=9D and opened the bags and found rocks.=
=C2=A0And then the LME dutifully reported that some nickel was not nickel, =
and JPMorgan=E2=80=99s nickel warrants were transformed into rocks warrants=
.
In a footnote, I clarified that I was just imagining this scenario, and tha=
t=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI have no idea how the fraud was discovered and never want =
to find out, unless the real story is funnier than this one.=E2=80=9D Do I =
have good news for you!   Bloomberg News reports:

The revelation that about $2 million of =E2=80=9Cnickel=E2=80=9D on the Lon=
don Metal Exchange was actually just bags of stones has thrown a spotlight =
on the sprawling web of warehouses and metal stashes underpinning the billi=
ons of dollars of derivatives traded daily on the LME.
Over the past week, warehouse staff from Busan in South Korea to Genoa in I=
taly have rushed to check tens of thousands of two-ton bags of nickel =E2=
=80=93 in some cases, by literally kicking them.
The LME advised warehouse operators to wear steel toe-capped boots for safe=
ty, one person who received the instructions said. The rule of thumb: If it=
 hurts when you kick it, it=E2=80=99s probably nickel.
The mass inspection, which also included more carefully calibrated checks l=
ike weighing and scanning the bags, came after the LME last week announced =
it had discovered =E2=80=9Cirregularities=E2=80=9D in nine nickel contracts=
.

That is extremely satisfying. Isn=E2=80=99t high finance great? One day you=
 are sitting at your computer using sophisticated software to trade million=
s of dollars of abstract financial contracts in milliseconds to bet on glob=
al macroeconomic conditions. Then your boss taps you on the shoulder and is=
 like =E2=80=9Chey sorry you have to leave the desk for a few days to go ki=
ck a few thousand bags of nickel.=E2=80=9D No no no I=E2=80=99m kidding, th=
e futures traders and nickel-kickers are different people, but they are all=
 interconnected in the elaborate system of global finance, which requires b=
oth high-speed data networks and also steel-toed boots for safety.
Also:

There are two possible explanations: either the bags were already full of s=
