<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Binance</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A decent rule of thumb is that all cryptocurre=
ncy exchanges are doing crimes, and if you=E2=80=99re lucky your exchange i=
s doing only process crimes.=C2=A0 Today the US Commodity Futures Trading C=
ommission <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30973470=
.267437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2Z0Yy5nb3YvUHJlc3NSb29tL1ByZXNzUmVsZWFzZXMvODY4MC0=
yMw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1f01bc7a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> sued Binance Holdings Ltd.<=
/a>, Changpeng Zhao=E2=80=99s big crypto derivatives exchange, for letting =
Americans trade crypto derivatives. There are no accusations that Binance i=
s stealing customer money, or even taking big risks with it, which makes Bi=
nance look better than <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/30973470.267437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbG=
VzLzIwMjItMTItMTMvaG93LXRvLWRvLWZyYXVkLWF0LWEtZnV0dXJlcy1leGNoYW5nZT9jbXBpZ=
D1CQkQwMzI3MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xl=
dHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMjcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB33aa730a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">
some other crypto exchanges</a> I could name. There are =E2=80=A6=C2=A0look=
, there are not=C2=A0<em>no=C2=A0</em>accusations that Binance is launderin=
g money for terrorists or secretly trading against its customers, but there=
 are relatively <em>few</em> accusations=C2=A0like that; again, as crypto e=
xchanges go, that=E2=80=99s pretty good.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">No, the CFTC=E2=80=99s case is mainly about le=
tting US customers trade crypto derivatives. It is illegal to run a crypto =
derivatives exchange in the US without registering it with the CFTC, and it=
=E2=80=99s not exactly easy to do that either; if you have a crypto derivat=
ives exchange abroad but have not registered it in the US,=C2=A0it is illeg=
al to let US customers trade on it. So the basic rule is that US customers =
can=E2=80=99t trade crypto derivatives, and big international crypto deriva=
tives exchanges (Binance,=C2=A0FTX before it blew up) sometimes have US-onl=
y platforms (Binance US, FTX.us) that let US customers trade a limited set =
of products, but not most=C2=A0derivatives.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For retail customers this is probably fine: A =
crypto exchange can make a bit more money from retail gamblers if it offers=
 them high-leverage futures trading, but there are plenty of gamblers in th=
e world, and also you can make decent money from US traders just by letting=
 them trade crypto for cash.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it is a problem for a big exchange, becaus=
e a lot of the big high-frequency market-making firms in financial markets =
happen to be in the US. If you want to run a global crypto exchange, or a g=
lobal crypto futures exchange, you will want the big New York and Chicago h=
igh-frequency trading firms to make markets on your exchange, because that =
will make your exchange more liquid and your prices more accurate. And they=
 will want to make markets on your exchange, because they will make more mo=
ney that way. And they are big institutional trading firms with offices aro=
und the world and plenty of Cayman Islands subsidiaries, so if you were to =
say to them=C2=A0=E2=80=9Chey technically we can=E2=80=99t offer our produc=
ts to Chicago residents=E2=80=9D they would=C2=A0say =E2=80=9Cno no no we a=
re residents of the world of global capital, not Chicago, it=E2=80=99s fine=
.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it is not fine! The <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30973470.267437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2Z0Yy5n=
b3YvbWVkaWEvODM1MS8lMjBlbmZiaW5hbmNlY29tcGxhaW50MDMyNzIzL2Rvd25sb2Fk/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB9838e2f1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> CFTC complaint</a> contains a certain=
 amount of retail-focused subterfuge. (Binance has a website that helps peo=
ple understand how to trade on Binance, and the website had an explanation =
of how to use a virtual private network to log into Binance without disclos=
ing that you are in the US, and the CFTC doesn=E2=80=99t like that.<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>) But what is striking about the complaint is that it is=C2=A0<em>mostl=
y=C2=A0</em>about how Binance offered trading services to large New York an=
d Chicago high-frequency trading firms through their offshore subsidiaries.=
 For instance<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background=
-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At some point before October 2020, Binance for=
malized its processes for instructing U.S. VIP customers on the best method=
s to evade Binance=E2=80=99s compliance controls in a corporate policy titl=
ed =E2=80=9CVIP Handling.=E2=80=9D Zhao contributed ideas that were incorpo=
rated into the VIP Handling policy. Pursuant to the VIP Handling policy, on=
ce a customer service representative =E2=80=9Chands the affected user over =
to VIP,=E2=80=9D the VIP team would =E2=80=9C[m]ake sure the user has compl=
eted his/her new account creation with no U.S. documents allowed.=E2=80=9D =
U.S. VIP customers often followed these instructions by submitting =E2=80=
=9Cnew=E2=80=9D KYC documentation associated with a shell company incorpora=
ted in a jurisdiction other than the United States, such as the British Vir=
gin Islands, to act as the nominee for the =E2=80=9Cnew=E2=80=9D account. =
=E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Binance=E2=80=99s VIP Handling policy also est=
ablished methods for Binance personnel to troubleshoot for U.S. customers t=
hat were identified as such through their IP address (as opposed to KYC doc=
umentation). For these customers, Binance instructed its personnel to =E2=
=80=9C[i]nform the user that the reason why he/she cant use our www.binance=
.com is because his/her IP is detected as US IP. If user doesn=E2=80=99t ge=
t the hint, indicate that IP is the sole reason why he/she can=E2=80=99t us=
e .com=E2=80=9D [emphasis in original]. Lim flagged a passage in the VIP Ha=
ndling policy for his colleagues that further explained: =E2=80=9CWe cannot=
 teach users how to circumvent the controls. If they figure it out on their=
 own, its fine.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Displaying the ecosystem=E2=80=99s tone at the=
 top, Zhao helped manage the implementation of Binance=E2=80=99s VIP Handli=
ng policy. On October 9, 2020, around the time Binance began sending emails=
 to U.S. customers pursuant to the policy, Zhao had the following exchange =
with an employee who would ultimately become Binance=E2=80=99s head of inst=
itutional sales:</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">VIP team member: Hi CZ . . . I went through li=
st of affected API clients, it includes a number of large strategic account=
s including [a Chicago-headquartered trading firm] who is currently is a to=
p 5 client and 12% of our volume</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Zhao: Give them a heads up to ensure they don=
=E2=80=99t connect from a us Ip. Don=E2=80=99t leave anything in writing. T=
hey have non us entities. Let=E2=80=99s also make sure we don=E2=80=99t hit=
 the biggest market makers with that email first. Do you have signal?</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, a US trading firm that was=C2=A0<em>1=
2% of Binance=E2=80=99s volume=C2=A0</em>was getting locked out of Binance=
=E2=80=99s application programming interface =E2=80=94=C2=A0the direct conn=
ection to Binance=E2=80=99s matching engine that high-frequency trading fir=
ms need to trade algorithmically =E2=80=94=C2=A0because it had a US IP addr=
ess. So Binance told it =E2=80=94=C2=A0not in writing! =E2=80=94=C2=A0to us=
e a VPN to connect.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a whole section of the complaint devo=
ted to =E2=80=9CExamples of Market Participants Currently Trading on Binanc=
e and Binance=E2=80=99s Efforts to Help Them Evade Its Compliance Controls.=
=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s worth quoting extensively, because these =E2=80=9Cma=
rket participants=E2=80=9D are not retail gamblers or Russian oligarchs, bu=
t multinational=C2=A0proprietary=C2=A0trading firms:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Trading Firm A is a quantitative trading firm =
that has traded bitcoin perpetuals on Binance, among other products, throug=
h at least three different accounts during the Relevant Period. Trading Fir=
m A is a Delaware limited liability company headquartered in Chicago, Illin=
ois. Trading Firm A also has offices in New York and Amsterdam. =E2=80=A6</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In June 2019, a Binance Key Account Manager in=
structed Trading Firm A to =E2=80=9Cswitch the account KYC.=E2=80=9D Follow=
ing Binance=E2=80=99s instructions, Trading Firm A opened a =E2=80=9Cnew=E2=
=80=9D Binance account in August 2019 in the name of a wholly-owned subsidi=
ary incorporated in the Cayman Islands. Substantially all personnel that pe=
rform work for this Cayman Islands nominee entity are employed by Trading F=
irm A or its subsidiaries and Trading Firm A controls all aspects of its Ca=
yman Islands subsidiary. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Trading Firm B is a quantitative trading firm =
headquartered in New York and incorporated in Delaware. Trading Firm B has =
at all relevant times been ultimately majority owned by U.S. residents. Num=
erous senior managers, including the individual who functions as Trading Fi=
rm B=E2=80=99s CEO, have worked from Trading Firm B=E2=80=99s New York head=
quarters. Trading Firm B also has offices in London, Amsterdam, Hong Kong, =
and Singapore. Trading Firm B uses =E2=80=9Cproxy servers=E2=80=9D to acces=
s the internet. Like VPNs, proxy servers obscure an internet user=E2=80=99s=
 true IP address.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Trading Firm B conducts its digital asset trad=
ing activity on Binance through a dedicated trading desk that utilizes auto=
mated trading strategies programmed into computer algorithms developed by p=
ersonnel at Trading Firm B=E2=80=99s New York headquarters, among other loc=
ations. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On March 11, 2022, Trading Firm B submitted KY=
C documents to Binance concerning an application for a =E2=80=9Cnew=E2=80=
=9D Binance account to be held by a nominee shell company organized under t=
he laws of Jersey. The shares of this new nominee entity are =E2=80=9Cowned=
=E2=80=9D by a third party that has no affiliation with Trading Firm B and =
does not exercise any control over Trading Firm B=E2=80=99s trading activit=
y on Binance.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Trading Firm B=E2=80=99s Jersey nominee does n=
ot have any employees and does not have any meaningful sources of capital, =
apart from Trading Firm B. Trading Firm B=E2=80=99s Jersey nominee has ente=
red into at least two contracts with Trading Firm B subsidiaries. First, a =
=E2=80=9CServices Agreement.=E2=80=9D Under the terms of that agreement, a =
Trading Firm B subsidiary agrees to provide office space, personnel, techno=
logy, information technology support, including maintenance of=C2=A0all ser=
vices and systems databases, and =E2=80=9Cany services as the parties may a=
gree from time to time.=E2=80=9D Second, a =E2=80=9CConfirmatory Note.=E2=
=80=9D Under the terms of that note, a Trading Firm B subsidiary agrees to =
transfer funds to Trading Firm B=E2=80=99s Jersey nominee for the purpose o=
f engaging in =E2=80=9CNominee Trading Activities.=E2=80=9D In return, Trad=
ing Firm B=E2=80=99s Jersey nominee agrees to provide Trading Firm B with t=
he =E2=80=9CNet Proceeds=E2=80=9D of its nominee trading activity on Binanc=
e.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Trading Firm B is a New York trading firm that=
 set up a Jersey entity to trade on Binance, and entered into an agreement =
to manage that entity=E2=80=99s trading. This is not some retail trader rea=
ding the Binance website and realizing that he can use a VPN to gamble on c=
rypto futures; this is a big algorithmic market maker with sophisticated la=
wyers who thought =E2=80=9Cwell obviously=C2=A0<em>we=E2=80=99re=C2=A0</em>=
allowed to trade on Binance even though we happen to live in New York, let=
=E2=80=99s just set up a Jersey company and get the documents in order.=E2=
=80=9D But the CFTC isn=E2=80=99t having it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The last few weeks have seen a wide-ranging an=
d aggressive US crackdown on crypto. In February, US banking regulators <a =
