<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hey <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/30973470.267437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2Fy=
dGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjcvZmlyc3QtY2l0aXplbnMtdG8tYnV5LXNpbGljb24tdmFsbGV5LWJ=
hbmstYWZ0ZXItcnVuLW9uLWxlbmRlcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzI3MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbW=
VkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMjcmdXRtX2Nhb=
XBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBafe54c5d" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  they so=
ld SVB</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">First Citizens BancShares Inc. agreed to buy S=
ilicon Valley Bank after a run on deposits wiped out the company in the big=
gest US bank failure in more than a decade.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The deal to settle SVB=E2=80=99s fate could he=
lp tamp down some of the turmoil that has engulfed the financial world, and=
 shares of regional banks rallied on the news, with First Citizens up 44%. =
The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. seized SVB earlier this month amid conc=
ern that bank runs could spread.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The acquisition transforms First Citizens into=
 one of the top 15 US banks, according to Bloomberg Intelligence, with help=
 from some favorable terms. First Citizens is buying about $72 billion of S=
VB=E2=80=99s assets at a discount of $16.5 billion, according to an FDIC st=
atement.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This leaves about $90 billion in securities an=
d other SVB assets in the hands of the FDIC, and an estimated cost of the f=
ailure to the Deposit Insurance Fund of about $20 billion. Meanwhile, the F=
DIC gets equity appreciation rights in First Citizens with a potential valu=
e of $500 million.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The financing of the deal is sort of fascinati=
ng.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tr=
ansparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0First Citizens is getting about $110.1 billion of assets, includi=
ng $35 billion of cash and $72 billion of loans. In exchange, it is putting=
 up zero dollars and assuming about $93.6 billion of liabilities, for a tot=
al purchase price for those assets of negative $16.5 billion.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The liabilities consist mainly of:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">$56.5 billion of SVB deposits, and</li=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">a $35 billion five-year promissory no=
te to the FDIC with 3.5% interest.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is also a series of deals to share the u=
pside and downside. On the downside, First Citizens bears the risk of the f=
irst $5 billion of losses on the portfolio, but the FDIC shares any additio=
nal losses 50/50. On the upside, if there=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>no additio=
nal losses, First Citizens has to give the FDIC some money back, up to $1.5=
 billion; the FDIC also gets a =E2=80=9Cvalue appreciation instrument=E2=80=
=9D giving it some upside in First Citizens=E2=80=99 stock, capped at $500 =
million.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-colo=
r: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Arguably <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/30973470.267437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGl=
uaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTAvc3RhcnR1cC1iYW5rLWhhZC1hLXN0YXJ0dXAtYmFuay=
1ydW4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMyNzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291c=
mNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzI3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB02235c73" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  the basic problem at SVB</a> was =
that it had a portfolio of long-term assets (loans, Treasury bonds, etc.) s=
upported by rickety short-term financing: SVB was funded mainly by deposits=
, almost all of which exceeded the FDIC=E2=80=99s deposit insurance cap of =
$250,000 per account. When depositors got nervous, they took out a lot of m=
oney all at once =E2=80=94=C2=A0$42 billion in one day =E2=80=94=C2=A0and S=
VB didn=E2=80=99t have enough money to pay them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic fix for this is pretty much to get s=
ome long-term funding =E2=80=94=C2=A0ideally=C2=A0<em>cheap=C2=A0</em>long-=
term funding, since SVB loaded up on long-dated assets back when interest r=
ates were very low, and would be losing money if it had to borrow at 5% to =
fund them. And that is in fact what happened. SVB=E2=80=99s $90 billion sec=
urities portfolio now belongs to the FDIC, which is the US government and g=
ets very cheap funding.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And its loan portfolio now belongs to First Ci=
tizens, which is paying for it by borrowing $35 billion from the FDIC for f=
ive years at 3.5% interest. As the loans pay off, First Citizens will send =
the money to the FDIC,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; b=
ackground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0but there is no rush; the long-term financing from the FDIC means=
 that First Citizens doesn=E2=80=99t need to worry about getting cash befor=
e its loans mature. Also the money is cheap: The US government can borrow f=
or five years at about 3.58%, but First Citizens is doing a bit better borr=
owing from the government.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course the other $56.5 billion of First Cit=
izens=E2=80=99 financing comes from SVB=E2=80=99s depositors who haven=E2=
=80=99t taken their money out yet. That =E2=80=A6=C2=A0might be shorter-ter=
m money?=C2=A0As of Dec. 31, 2022, Silicon Valley Bank had about $173 billi=
on of deposits,=C2=A0of which about $165 billion were not insured by the Fe=
deral Deposit Insurance Corp., mostly because they exceeded the $250,000 ca=
p on FDIC insurance.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0As of this morning, after its bank run, it had about $56.5 billio=
n of deposits. I don=E2=80=99t know how many of those deposits are uninsure=
d, but I would be surprised if people were flocking=C2=A0<em>to=C2=A0</em>S=
ilicon Valley bank to deposit money in the last couple of weeks, so my gues=
s is that no more than $8 billion of deposits (the rough number as of Dec. =
31) are insured, and the remaining $48.5 billion are not. For the last two =
weeks, SVB has been,=C2=A0<em>and has <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/30973470.267437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGl=
uaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTUvc2lsaWNvbi12YWxsZXktYmFuay1pcy1mb3Itc2FsZT=
9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzI3MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9b=
mV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMjcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB462ae64c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  advertised itself as</a></em>, the saf=
est bank in the US: It was essentially the only bank where all deposits, ev=
en those way above the FDIC=E2=80=99s $250,000 deposit-insurance cap, were =
guaranteed by the FDIC.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-8" sty=
