<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My model of electricity markets is that they a=
re a weird combination of:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Markets designed by economists to ach=
ieve their wildest theoretical fantasies of matching supply and demand in p=
erfect competition, tied to</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A part=
icularly formidable set of real-world problems about shoveling coal into gi=
ant boilers to generate electricity.=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B</l=
i>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so power markets are way better and more r=
uthless than, like, Uber at surge pricing: Electricity is very cheap when d=
emand is low, and=C2=A0very expensive when demand is high. And this is all =
very tidy and rational and economists write nice papers about it, because t=
he high prices at peak demand do attract more capacity and enable the grid =
to function. But also if electricity prices shoot up by 100% in five second=
s, you can=E2=80=99t just turn on a coal power plant to meet demand. You ha=
ve to call workers to go to the plant, and turn on the lights, and shovel t=
he coal into the boiler, and it all takes time.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so a good set of tricks in electricity tra=
ding involves=C2=A0<em>getting paid peak prices for non-peak generation</em=
>, because your plants take a long time to turn on and off. One of my all-t=
ime favorite trades is a series of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/30973470.267437/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZWFsYnJlYWtlci5jb20vMjAxMy8wNy=
9lbGVjdHJpY2l0eS1tYXJrZXQtcnVsZXMtd2VyZS1ub3QtYS13b3J0aHktb3Bwb25lbnQtZm9yL=
WpwbW9yZ2Fucy1icmFpbnBvd2Vy/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB99a6751d" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">powe=
r market manipulations</a> that JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. did more than a de=
cade ago. One of the trades went like this:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The system takes bids in hourly increm=
ents.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You offer electricity at the=
 lowest price for some hour, say 2 to 3 p.m.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bot=
tom: 5px;">The system accepts your bid and relies on you to generate electr=
icity.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You offer electricity at a =
very high price for the hour before and the hour after your hour, 1 to 2 an=
d 3 to 4 p.m.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The system says =E2=
=80=9Cah well it takes time to turn a plant on and off, so if we use you fo=
r the 2-to-3 hour, we need to also pay you for the 1-to-2 and 3-to-4 hours,=
=E2=80=9D and it pays you your very high offer price for those hours.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a good trick, though really it is just=
 bad design of the system that chose providers based on each hour=E2=80=99s=
 price rather than the overall cost. (JPMorgan paid a big fine for this.)</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Gavin Finch, Jason Grotto =
and Todd Gillespie have a story about UK power traders who basically threat=
en=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>to generate electricity at peak hours unless they=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30973470.267437/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9ncmFwaGljcy8yMDIzLXVrLXBvd2VyLWVsZWN0cmlj=
aXR5LW1hcmtldC1tYW5pcHVsYXRpbmcvP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMjcyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9=
tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDMyNyZ1dG1fY2=
FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB687620ab" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> get pa=
id peak prices for their non-peak generation</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In times of especially high demand, operators =
call on older, gas- and coal-fired plants that rarely find it cost-effectiv=
e to operate in normal conditions. Only a handful of producers =E2=80=94 in=
cluding Vitol=E2=80=99s VPI, which owns five gas-powered plants in the UK =
=E2=80=94 operate such facilities, giving them real market power in the bal=
ancing mechanism when conditions get stressed. Nearly 75% of the =C2=A3525 =
million captured by Bloomberg=E2=80=99s analysis came on tight days when th=
e grid would have already been under pressure.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Moreover, gas plants are unwieldy; they typica=
lly take about six hours to cool down before they can run again =E2=80=94 a=
nd Ofgem said power traders use that inflexibility to their advantage. By t=
elling the grid they will power down before the daily demand peak =E2=80=94=
 between 5 and 6 p.m. =E2=80=94 traders are putting the grid operator in a =
bind. If a plant goes offline, it=E2=80=99s lost for the rest of the day. S=
o, to keep it available for the evening, the grid operator must agree to ac=
cept its offer of electricity via the balancing mechanism beginning at arou=
nd lunchtime =E2=80=94 and pay higher-than-normal prices for hours longer t=
han necessary.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a sense in which this is all economic=
ally rational: If you were designing an electric power market, you would=C2=
=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>to give peaker owners enough incentive to keep their =
plants on during lower-demand hours so that they are available to meet high=
er demand later. But the actual mechanism =E2=80=94=C2=A0they agree to prov=
ide electricity at normal rates during low-demand hours, then say =E2=80=9C=
haha no we=E2=80=99re turning off, see you tomorrow,=E2=80=9D and then get =
paid a premium to stay on =E2=80=94=C2=A0seems not ideal.</p>
