319a23cB8825f325" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">  talked last week</a> about the discovery that s=
ome nickel belonging to JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co., which it used to support =
nickel futures trading on the London Metal Exchange, was actually just rock=
s. The nickel =E2=80=94=C2=A0I mean, rocks =E2=80=94 had been sitting in an=
 LME-affiliated warehouse for years; its role in life was to support nickel=
 futures trading, not to be turned into batteries or cars or whatever. =E2=
=80=9CThe nickel worked perfectly well for those purposes =E2=80=94 JPMorga=
n=E2=80=99s derivative contracts traded and paid off normally =E2=80=94 for=
 years, even though the nickel was not in fact nickel, just bags of rocks,=
=E2=80=9D I wrote. I went on:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then one day a warehouse worke=
r, like, stubbed his toe against JPMorgan=E2=80=99s nickel and was like =E2=
=80=9Chmm that=E2=80=99s not the sound nickel makes when you kick it=E2=80=
=9D and opened the bags and found rocks.=C2=A0And then the LME dutifully re=
ported that some nickel was not nickel, and JPMorgan=E2=80=99s nickel warra=
nts were transformed into rocks warrants.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a footnote, I clarified that I was just ima=
gining this scenario, and that=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI have no idea how the fraud w=
as discovered and never want to find out, unless the real story is funnier =
than this one.=E2=80=9D Do I have good news for you! <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30973470.267437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjQvbG1lLW5pY2tlbC10aGUtbXlzdGVyeS1=
iZWhpbmQtanBtb3JnYW4tcy1iYWdzLW9mLXN0b25lcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzI3MjNfTU9ORVlTVF=
VGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzM=
jcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9ff0c3c7" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">  Bloomberg News reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The revelation that about $2 million of =E2=80=
=9Cnickel=E2=80=9D on the London Metal Exchange was actually just bags of s=
tones has thrown a spotlight on the sprawling web of warehouses and metal s=
tashes underpinning the billions of dollars of derivatives traded daily on =
the LME.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over the past week, warehouse staff from Busan=
 in South Korea to Genoa in Italy have rushed to check tens of thousands of=
 two-ton bags of nickel =E2=80=93 in some cases, by literally kicking them.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The LME advised warehouse operators to wear st=
eel toe-capped boots for safety, one person who received the instructions s=
aid. The rule of thumb: If it hurts when you kick it, it=E2=80=99s probably=
 nickel.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The mass inspection, which also included more =
carefully calibrated checks like weighing and scanning the bags, came after=
 the LME last week announced it had discovered =E2=80=9Cirregularities=E2=
=80=9D in nine nickel contracts.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is extremely satisfying. Isn=E2=80=99t hi=
gh finance great? One day you are sitting at your computer using sophistica=
ted software to trade millions of dollars of abstract financial contracts i=
n milliseconds to bet on global macroeconomic conditions. Then your boss ta=
ps you on the shoulder and is like =E2=80=9Chey sorry you have to leave the=
 desk for a few days to go kick a few thousand bags of nickel.=E2=80=9D No =
no no I=E2=80=99m kidding, the futures traders and nickel-kickers are diffe=
rent people, but they are all interconnected in the elaborate system of glo=
bal finance, which requires both high-speed data networks and also steel-to=
ed boots for safety.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are two possible explanations: either th=
e bags were already full of stones when they were first delivered into Acce=
ss World=E2=80=99s Rotterdam warehouse, or someone sneaked into the warehou=
se to steal the nickel.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Access World is leaning toward the second theo=
ry, according to people familiar with the matter, because it has a record o=
f the material being weighed when it first entered the warehouse.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">See I would have assumed that stealing nickel =
and substituting rocks=C2=A0<em>in transit=C2=A0</em>would make a lot of se=
nse, while=C2=A0<em>sneaking into a warehouse to bring in rocks and take ou=
t nickel </em>would be insane, but (1) what do I know and (2) I am desperat=
e to see the movie of this.</p>
